  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "Two events are independent if knowing that one occurred tells you nothing about whether the other occurred. You flip a fair coin twice: whether the first flip lands heads is independent of whether the second lands heads — the coin has no memory. You draw a card from a deck, replace it, shuffle, and draw again: the two draws are independent. But draw without replacing: now the draws are dependent, because the first draw changes what remains in the deck.\n",
  "name": "Independence",
